font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=371.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_tongue.gif" align=absmiddle>  Roawen...</span><hr size=1> Well I am an ex smoker... I also know many considerate smokers, much like you.  Hell I know a guy that goes outside to smoke from bars....<br>
<br>
As an ex smoker I feel your pain as well.  I smoked for about 7 years, then half smoked for several more.  Quit for a month or two, pick it back up. Blend, rinse, repeat.  Those scowling ex-smokers that pass by you are scowling because the merest wiff of tobacco makes them salivate... I know this.  It was years (about 5 or 6) after I finally quit  before I stopped wanting a smoke everytime I drank a  beer, smelled cigarrette smoke, or saw a glossy magazine ad.  Thats what makes the ex-smoker so much a nazi... The slightest temperance leads to relapse.  So forgive us if you can, we at least know what you are going through.<br>
<br>
Non-smokers who scowl have no clue (or at least no conception of what this means) that the addiction you are battling is harder to break than Heroin (documented).  Many, many smokers would quit if only they could without extreme physical and mental  discomfort.   Keep this in mind if/when you decide to quit.  Get  a support group, hypnosis, some nicotine gum/patch, it is very hard to do cold turkey and on your own.  You will almost certainly fail if your roommate/SO do not also quit, and you may have to avoid bars for awhile if smoking is allowed in those in your area.<br>
<br>
&lt;sigh&gt;  Even after being 14 yrs without a smoke I still get a twinge now and then... <p>Lorec <br>
